SIMPLE: insipid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insipid
<hw>In*sip"id</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>insipidus</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> not + <ets>sapidus</ets>
savory, fr. <ets>sapere</ets> to taste: cf. F. <ets>insipide</ets>. See
<er>Savor</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Wanting in the qualities which affect the organs of
taste; without taste or savor; vapid; tasteless; <as>as,
<ex>insipid</ex> drink or food</as>.</def> <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Wanting in spirit, life, or animation;
uninteresting; weak; vapid; flat; dull; heavy; <as>as, an
<ex>insipid</ex> woman; an <ex>insipid</ex> composition.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Flat, <qex>insipid</qex>, and ridiculous stuff to him.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But his wit is faint, and his salt, if I may dare to say so,
almost <qex>insipid</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Tasteless; vapid; dull; spiritless; unanimated;
lifeless; flat; stale; pointless; uninteresting.</syn></p>

<p><ent>Insipidness</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Insipidity</ent>⟦br⟧
